0    RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM

As indicated earlier, REC pro-actively implements the RPP for the SCR ammonia system. The scope of the RPP encompasses various facets of release prevention; e.g., it enhances employee participation, increases employee awareness about the hazards of handling ammonia, establishes safe standard operating procedures, and enhances access to process safety inf ormation through annual training being provided by the vendor, as well as hands-on training. RMP training records are included in Exhibit F of this RMP.



During the design process, REC performed a hazards analysis on the SCR ammonia system. Subsequent hazard reviews were performed after three (3) years and again after five (5) years to review the existing operating procedures and equipment maintenance schedule. These operational safeguard measures indicate a high success rate as demonstrated through no reported leaks or releases.



The RPP provides the procedural backbone for safe operability functions and allows REC to maintain, review and evaluate the program on a periodic basis. Basic elements include the following but are not limited to:



?    Annual personnel training ( Exhibit F);

?    Hands-on training to new employees ( Exhibit F);

?    Ammonia release sensors located in the tanks area, which gives an alarm in the control room when triggered;

?    "Daily round" inspections by shif t workers once per shift (at least twice daily);

?    Annual calibration of the ammonia sensors ( Exhibit E);

?    Ammonia pumps are shutdown when the combustion turbines are not generating;

?    Facility personnel are required to follow a chemical off-loading procedure and checklist;

?    Continuous review of safe operating procedures;

?    Evaluation of  the mechanical  integrity  of  the equipment which includes visual inspection of the ammonia tank every three (3) years;

?    Implementation    of    a    preventive    maintenance    schedule    per    vendor's recommendations;  and

?    Effective emergency response program.



